The paper deals with counterexample-guided abstraction refinement (CEGAR) for probabilistic programs, which involves abstract interpretation and abstract domains. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with probabilistic programming languages (PPLs), which suggests that it could belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. The paper also discusses refinement techniques, which suggests that it could belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The paper deals with loop invariants, which suggests that it could belong to the Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with abstract interpretation, which suggests that it could belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.
